  "prompt": "Why does hair turn grey as people age?",
  "response": "Hair turns grey as people age primarily due to a decrease in the production of melanin, the pigment responsible for the color of hair, skin, and eyes. Here\u2019s a more detailed explanation of the process:\n\n1. **Melanin Production**: Hair color is determined by the type and amount of melanin produced by melanocytes, which are specialized cells located in the hair follicles. There are two types of melanin: eumelanin (which can be black or brown) and pheomelanin (which is yellow or red). The combination of these pigments gives hair its natural color.\n\n2. **Aging and Melanocyte Activity**: As people age, the melanocytes in hair follicles gradually decrease in number and become less active. This results in the production of less melanin and, ultimately, the hair follicles may stop producing pigment altogether.\n\n3. **Genetics**: The age at which a person\u2019s hair begins to turn grey is largely determined by genetics. Some individuals may notice grey hair in their 20s, while others may not see it until much later.\n\n4. **Oxidative Stress**: There is also research suggesting that oxidative stress\u2014caused by free radicals that damage cells\u2014might play a role in the aging of melanocytes, contributing to the greying process.\n\n5. **Health and Lifestyle Factors**: Other factors, such as stress, nutritional deficiencies, smoking, and certain medical conditions, can also influence the greying of hair, although these factors vary in their impact from person to person.\n\nIn summary, the greying of hair is a natural part of aging, influenced by genetic, biological, and environmental factors.",
